'''Paul Landowski''' (1 June 1875 – 31 March 1961) was a French monument sculptor of Polish descent, best known for creating the iconic [Christ the Redeemer_(statue)] in [Rio de Janeiro](/Rio_de_Janeiro), Brazil. His artistic output combined classical technique with a distinctly Art Deco sensibility, producing works that remain prominent in public spaces across Europe and the Americas.  

== Biography ==
Landowski was born in [Paris](/Paris) to a Polish father, a refugee of the [January_Uprising](/January_Uprising), and a French mother, Julie Vieuxtemps, who came from a family of artists. He received his early artistic training at the [Académie Julian](/Académie_Julian) and later graduated from the prestigious [École nationale supérieure des Beaux-Arts](/École_nationale_sup%C3%A9rieure_des_Beaux-Arts). In 1900 he won the coveted [Prix de Rome](/Prix_de_Rome) with his sculpture of [David](/David), a triumph that launched a career spanning more than five decades.

During his formative years he produced a series of public monuments that blended mythological themes with contemporary civic ideals. Notable among these is the [Art Deco](/Art_Deco) figure of [St. Genevi%C3%A8ve](/St._Genevi%C3%A8ve) perched on the 1928 [Pont de la Tournelle](/Pont_de_la_Tournelle). The bridge, spanning the Seine, showcases Landowski’s ability to integrate sculpture with architectural context, a skill that would later inform his most famous collaboration.

== World War I service ==
When [World War I](/World_War_I) erupted, Landowski enlisted and fought in the brutal [Battle of the Somme](/Battle_of_the_Somme). His valor earned him the Citation of the Order of the Artillery Brigade and the distinguished [Croix de Guerre](/Croix_de_Guerre). The trauma of the conflict profoundly influenced his subsequent work; in the immediate post‑armistice period he created ''Les Fantômes'', a memorial to the [Second_Battle_of_the_Marne](/Second_Battle_of_the_Marne) that stands on the Butte de Chalmont in Northern France. He also produced two major [Monuments_aux_Morts](/Monuments_aux_Morts) in [French North Africa](/French_North_Africa)—the first, known as Le Pavois in [Algiers](/Algiers), was later concealed behind the [Memorial_to_the_Liberation_of_Algeria](/Memorial_to_the_Liberation_of_Algeria) in 1978; the second, a monument to victory and peace in [Casablanca](/Casablanca), was originally sited on today's [Mohammed_V_Square](/Mohammed_V_Square) before being relocated to France in 1961 and re‑erected in [Senlis](/Senlis)). {{fact|date=June 2024}}  

== Major works ==
Landowski’s oeuvre includes more than thirty‑five monuments in Paris and a further twelve in the surrounding region. Among his most celebrated pieces are:

* The [Christ the Redeemer_(statue)] (1931) in [Rio de Janeiro](/Rio_de_Janeiro), Brazil—a collaborative effort with civil engineer [Heitor da Silva Costa](/Heitor_da_Silva_Costa) and sculptor [Gheorghe Leonida](/Gheorghe_Leonida). While Landowski designed the head and hands, the overall execution involved a team of artisans, and the head was ultimately refined by Leonida at Landowski’s request.  
* The bronze sculpture ''The Boxer'', which earned a gold medal at the [Art competitions at the 1928 Summer Olympics](/Art_competitions_at_the_1928_Summer_Olympics) for Sculpture, part of the broader [Art competitions at the summer Olympics](/Art_competitions_at_the_Summer_Olympics) that ran from 1912 to 1952. {{citation needed}}  
* Public monuments such as the [St. Genevi%C3%A8ve] figure on the [Pont de la Tournelle] and numerous commemorative statues across France, including memorials in [Algiers] and [Casablanca] that were later moved for preservation.

His artistic achievements were recognized internationally, leading to his appointment as Director of the [French Academy in Rome](/French_Academy_in_Rome) from 1933 to 1937. In this capacity he oversaw the training of a new generation of sculptors and also served as an art‑juror for the [Prix Blumenthal](/Prix_Blumenthal), a grant that supported young French creators between 1919 and 1954.  

== Personal life ==
Landowski married Geneviève Nénot in 1907; the couple had two children, painter Nadine Landowski (1908–1943) and agricultural engineer Jean Maximilian Landowski (1911–1944), both of whom perished during World War II. Geneviève died in 1912, after which Landowski married Amélie Cruppi. Their children were composer [Marcel Landowski](/Marcel_Landowski) (1915–1999) and pianist‑painter [Françoise Landowski-Caillet](/Fran%C3%A7oise_Landowski-Caillet) (1917–2007).  

In 1961, after suffering a heart attack, Landowski died in [Boulogne-Billancourt](/Boulogne-Billancourt), a suburb of Paris. A museum dedicated to his work now houses more than one hundred of his sculptures, drawings, and plaster models, offering visitors an comprehensive view of his artistic evolution.  

== Legacy ==
Landowski’s contribution to public art endures through the continued presence of his monuments in civic spaces, academic curricula, and cultural exhibitions. Scholars frequently cite his ability to fuse classical form with modernist aesthetics as a pivotal influence on 20th‑century French sculpture. His works are regularly featured in surveys of [[Category:French_sculptors]] and have inspired numerous contemporary artists who seek to balance narrative depth with formal precision.  

